Note:
R Parser - Parse R source code into Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)

This file implements a complete parser for the R statistical computing language.
Handles all R-specific syntax including vectorized operations, formulas, special
operators, and R data structures.

R-Specific Features:
- Assignment operators: <-, <<-, ->, ->>, =
- Pipe operators: |> (native R 4.1+), %>% (magrittr)
- Custom infix operators: %anything%
- Formula syntax: y ~ x1 + x2
- Accessor operators: $, @, ::, :::
- Indexing: [...], [[...]]
- Vectorized and short-circuit logical operators
- Special values: NA, NULL, NaN, Inf, TRUE, FALSE
- Function definitions with default args and varargs (...)
- Data structures: vectors, lists, data frames, matrices

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/r/r_lexer.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/r/r_lexer.runa" as RLexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note:
============================================================================
R AST CONTRACT (LOCKED) - the shape r_to_hir.runa must consume
============================================================================

Every AST node is a 72-byte ASTNode record. Field offsets are invariant:
    0  node_type     One of the NODE_* constants below
    8  value         String pointer for leaf nodes (lexeme / name / number text)
    16 left          Primary child (object / callee / target / lhs / package)
    24 right         Secondary child (operand / value / member / name / body)
    32 children      Pointer to a heap array of child node pointers
    40 child_count   Number of entries in the children array
    48 line          Source line
    56 column        Source column
    64 token_type    Original operator/flag token (BINARY_OP/UNARY_OP/ASSIGN/
                     NAMESPACE store the originating RLexer.TOKEN_* here)

Per-node-kind field usage (what r_to_hir reads):
    NODE_NUMBER / NODE_COMPLEX / NODE_STRING / NODE_IDENTIFIER:
        value(8) = lexeme/name string.
    NODE_TRUE / NODE_FALSE / NODE_NULL / NODE_NA / NODE_NAN / NODE_INF:
        no payload (kind alone carries meaning).
    NODE_BINARY_OP: left(16), right(24), token_type(64)=operator RLexer.TOKEN_*.
    NODE_UNARY_OP:  right(24)=operand, token_type(64)=operator RLexer.TOKEN_*.
    NODE_ASSIGN:    left(16)=target, right(24)=value. (Default-arg params reuse
                    this: left=param name identifier, right=default expr.)
    NODE_CALL:      left(16)=callee, children(32)/child_count(40)=arguments.
    NODE_INDEX:     left(16)=object, children(32)/child_count(40)=indices.
    NODE_DOUBLE_INDEX: left(16)=object, right(24)=single index.
    NODE_MEMBER_ACCESS / NODE_SLOT_ACCESS: left(16)=object,
                    right(24)=member/slot identifier node (NODE_IDENTIFIER).
    NODE_NAMESPACE: left(16)=package id, right(24)=name id,
                    token_type(64)=is_internal flag (0 for ::, 1 for :::).
    NODE_FORMULA:   left(16)=response, right(24)=predictors.
    NODE_FUNCTION_DEF / NODE_LAMBDA: children(32)/child_count(40)=parameters
                    (bare NODE_IDENTIFIER, or NODE_ASSIGN for defaults),
                    right(24)=body statement.
    NODE_VECTOR:    children(32)/child_count(40)=elements (c(...)).
    NODE_IF_STMT:   children[0]=condition, children[1]=then, children[2]=else
                    (else present only when child_count > 2).
    NODE_WHILE_STMT: children[0]=condition, children[1]=body.
    NODE_FOR_STMT:  children[0]=loop var id, children[1]=sequence, children[2]=body.
    NODE_REPEAT_STMT: children[0]=body.
    NODE_RETURN_STMT: right(24)=value (0 when bare return).
    NODE_BREAK_STMT / NODE_NEXT_STMT: no payload.
    NODE_EXPRESSION_STMT: left(16)=wrapped expression.
    NODE_BLOCK / NODE_PROGRAM: children(32)/child_count(40)=statements.

Entry points:
    parse_r_source(source) -> NODE_PROGRAM root (full lex + parse driver).
    tokenize_all(source, count_out) -> contiguous RToken array (lexer bridge).
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant NODE_PROGRAM as Integer is 9000
Constant NODE_EXPRESSION_STMT as Integer is 9001
Constant NODE_RETURN_STMT as Integer is 9002
Constant NODE_IF_STMT as Integer is 9003
Constant NODE_WHILE_STMT as Integer is 9004
Constant NODE_FOR_STMT as Integer is 9005
Constant NODE_REPEAT_STMT as Integer is 9006
Constant NODE_BREAK_STMT as Integer is 9007
Constant NODE_NEXT_STMT as Integer is 9008
Constant NODE_BLOCK as Integer is 9009

Note: Expression nodes
Constant NODE_BINARY_OP as Integer is 9010
Constant NODE_UNARY_OP as Integer is 9011
Constant NODE_ASSIGN as Integer is 9012
Constant NODE_CALL as Integer is 9013
Constant NODE_INDEX as Integer is 9014
Constant NODE_DOUBLE_INDEX as Integer is 9015
Constant NODE_MEMBER_ACCESS as Integer is 9016
Constant NODE_SLOT_ACCESS as Integer is 9017
Constant NODE_NAMESPACE as Integer is 9018
Constant NODE_FORMULA as Integer is 9019
Constant NODE_FUNCTION_DEF as Integer is 9020
Constant NODE_LAMBDA as Integer is 9021
Constant NODE_PIPE as Integer is 9022

Note: Literals
Constant NODE_NUMBER as Integer is 9030
Constant NODE_STRING as Integer is 9031
Constant NODE_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 9032
Constant NODE_TRUE as Integer is 9033
Constant NODE_FALSE as Integer is 9034
Constant NODE_NULL as Integer is 9035
Constant NODE_NA as Integer is 9036
Constant NODE_NAN as Integer is 9037
Constant NODE_INF as Integer is 9038
Constant NODE_COMPLEX as Integer is 9039

Note: Data structures
Constant NODE_VECTOR as Integer is 9040
Constant NODE_LIST as Integer is 9041
Constant NODE_DATAFRAME as Integer is 9042
Constant NODE_MATRIX as Integer is 9043

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
RParser holds an immutable view over the lexer's token array plus a moving cursor and recovery flags. Panic_mode is a Pratt-style recovery state: once tripped, the parser consumes until a synchronization token before re-attempting parses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five 8-byte fields, total 40 bytes, accessed via Layout offsets 0,8,16,24,32. tokens is a borrowed pointer to the lexer's heap-allocated token array.
@End Implementation

Type called "RParser":
    tokens as Integer       Note: Token array
    token_count as Integer  Note: Number of tokens
    current as Integer      Note: Current token index
    had_error as Integer    Note: Error flag
    panic_mode as Integer   Note: Panic mode for error recovery
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASTNode is a unified representation for every R syntactic construct - expressions, statements, function definitions, formulas. Both binary (left/right) and n-ary (children array) shapes are present so binary operators don't pay the cost of an array allocation while function calls and blocks can scale to arbitrary arity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Nine 8-byte fields, total 72 bytes, at offsets 0..64. Left/right are direct child pointers; children is a heap-grown array of pointers with child_count as its length. Token_type retains the original operator token for AST consumers that need to distinguish + from - etc.
@End Implementation

Type called "ASTNode":
    node_type as Integer    Note: Type of AST node
    value as Integer        Note: Associated value (string, number, etc.)
    left as Integer         Note: Left child
    right as Integer        Note: Right child
    children as Integer     Note: Array of children
    child_count as Integer  Note: Number of children
    line as Integer         Note: Source line number
    column as Integer       Note: Source column number
    token_type as Integer   Note: Original token type (for operators)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates an RParser cursor over a pre-existing token array. The token array is borrowed - it must remain valid for the parser's lifetime. Cursor starts at 0 with both error flags cleared.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes via Layout, writes tokens pointer, token_count, and zeroes current/had_error/panic_mode. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Returns heap-allocated parser; caller must destroy_parser. Does not assume ownership of the tokens array.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_parser" takes tokens as Integer, token_count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create parser with token array

    @Reasoning:
    Initialize parser state with the token stream from the lexer.
    Tracks current position and error state for parsing.
    @End Reasoning

    Let parser_size be 40  Note: RParser: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: current = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: had_error = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0  Note: panic_mode = 0

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the RParser block. Does not free the tokens array (borrowed) nor any AST nodes (those are owned by the caller's AST). Null-tolerant for failure-path destruction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-checks then calls Layout.deallocate. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy parser and free memory

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Bridge: Tokenize Whole Source Into A Contiguous Array
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The R lexer (r_lexer.runa) emits one RToken at a time as a separately-allocated
40-byte record, but RParser indexes its token stream as a single contiguous
array (tokens + index*40). tokenize_all bridges the two: it drives the lexer to
exhaustion and copies each 40-byte token into a contiguous, growable buffer so
the parser's pointer arithmetic is valid. The trailing EOF token is included so
current_token returns it (rather than 0) at the end of input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an RLexer over source, then repeatedly calls RLexer.next_token, copying
each token's 40 bytes into a contiguous array that doubles when full. Stops after
copying the EOF token. Writes the final element count through the count_out
pointer (an 8-byte caller-allocated cell) and returns the array base pointer.
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_all" takes source as Integer, count_out as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex the entire source into a contiguous array of 40-byte RTokens

    Let lexer be proc create_r_lexer from RLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let capacity be 64
    Let token_size be 40
    Let array be proc allocate from Layout with capacity multiplied by token_size
    If array is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_r_lexer from RLexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be 0
    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let tok be proc next_token from RLexer with lexer
        If tok is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
        Otherwise:
            Note: Grow the array if full
            If count is greater than or equal to capacity:
                Let new_capacity be capacity multiplied by 2
                Let new_array be proc allocate from Layout with new_capacity multiplied by token_size
                If new_array is equal to 0:
                    proc destroy_r_lexer from RLexer with lexer
                    Return 0
                End If
                Let copy_bytes be count multiplied by token_size
                Let b be 0
                While b is less than copy_bytes:
                    Let byte_val be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with array, b
                    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_array, b, byte_val
                    Set b to b plus 1
                End While
                proc deallocate from Layout with array
                Set array to new_array
                Set capacity to new_capacity
            End If

            Note: Copy the 40-byte token into slot `count`
            Let dest be array plus count multiplied by token_size
            Let field0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tok, 0
            Let field1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tok, 8
            Let field2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tok, 16
            Let field3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tok, 24
            Let field4 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tok, 32
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dest, 0, field0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dest, 8, field1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dest, 16, field2
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dest, 24, field3
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dest, 32, field4
            Set count to count plus 1

            Note: Stop after copying the EOF token
            If field0 is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Set looping to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc destroy_r_lexer from RLexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with count_out, 0, count

    Return array
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-call driver for the whole R frontend pipeline: source text in, AST root
out. This is the entry point that tests and r_to_hir use, so they never have to
hand-assemble the lexer/array/parser triple themselves.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an 8-byte count cell, calls tokenize_all to materialise the token
array, constructs a parser over (array, count) via create_parser, runs
parse_program, destroys the parser (the AST it produced is independent of the
parser record), and returns the program AST root. Returns 0 if tokenisation or
parser construction fails.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_r_source" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex + parse an R source string into a program AST

    Let count_cell be proc allocate from Layout with 8
    If count_cell is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with count_cell, 0, 0

    Let tokens be proc tokenize_all with source, count_cell
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with count_cell
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with count_cell, 0
    proc deallocate from Layout with count_cell

    Let parser be proc create_parser with tokens, token_count
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let program be proc parse_program with parser

    proc destroy_parser with parser

    Return program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocation point for every AST node so the 72-byte layout and field offsets stay invariant across all parse_* routines. All non-type fields are zeroed; parsers fill them in as needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 72 bytes via Layout, writes node_type at offset 0, zeros all other 8 fields explicitly. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Returns heap-allocated node; ownership transfers to the AST tree being built. Each node may grow a children array via add_child which adds further heap allocations.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new AST node

    Let node_size be 72  Note: ASTNode: 9 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: left
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: right
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: token_type

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a child pointer to the parent's variable-length children array. Uses naive grow-by-one realloc so the resulting array length equals child_count exactly - simpler than amortised doubling but more allocator traffic; acceptable here because R AST nodes rarely have more than a handful of children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates first slot lazily on first child. Subsequent calls allocate a new buffer of child_count+1 pointers, copy existing entries via a manual loop, deallocate the old buffer, then store the new child at index child_count and bump child_count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) per append due to copy; cumulative O(n^2) for n appends. Acceptable for shallow R syntax (call args, block statements). For very wide nodes (large block bodies) this could be hot.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 40

    Note: Allocate or resize children array
    If children is equal to 0:
        Let new_children be proc allocate from Layout with 8
        If new_children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, new_children
        Set children to new_children
    Otherwise:
        Let new_size be child_count plus 1
        Let new_size_bytes be new_size multiplied by 8
        Set new_children to proc allocate from Layout with new_size_bytes

        If new_children is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Copy existing children
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with new_children, i multiplied by 8, child_ptr
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, new_children
        Set children to new_children
    End If

    Note: Add new child
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children, child_count multiplied by 8, child
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 40, child_count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returns a pointer into the token array at the current cursor position. Returns 0 at end-of-stream so callers can use a single null-check sentinel for EOF detection.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads tokens base pointer, current index, and token_count. Bounds-checks then returns tokens + current * 40 (token size is 40 bytes - matches RToken layout from r_lexer).
@End Implementation

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If current is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_ptr be tokens plus current multiplied by 40  Note: Token size is 40 bytes

    Return token_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead helper for grammars that need to disambiguate beyond one token (e.g. `<- function (` vs `<-` followed by expression). Caller specifies absolute offset from cursor; 0 is equivalent to current_token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Adds offset to current index, bounds-checks, then returns tokens + (current+offset) * 40. Returns 0 if peek goes past token_count.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token" takes parser as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead at token

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    Let peek_pos be current plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_ptr be tokens plus peek_pos multiplied by 40

    Return token_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unconditional cursor bump. Callers are responsible for verifying the current token is acceptable before advancing; consume() pairs verification with advance for the common case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current index, writes current+1 back. Does not bounds-check - relies on current_token returning 0 at EOF.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming type check used by all the parse_* dispatchers that need to decide between alternatives without committing. Pair with advance() to consume after a successful match.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Fetches current_token, returns 0 if EOF, otherwise compares the token's type field (offset 0) against the requested type and returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation

Process called "match_token" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches type

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If type is equal to token_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Strict "must be this token" enforcement: succeeds and advances on match, otherwise sets had_error/panic_mode and emits the provided diagnostic message. Used at mandatory grammar positions (closing brackets, expected delimiters).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls match_token. On success, calls advance and returns the consumed token. On failure, sets had_error to 1, sets panic_mode to 1, and returns 0 - lifting recovery responsibility to the calling parse rule.
@End Implementation

Process called "consume" takes parser as Integer, token_type as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume token of expected type or error

    Let matches be proc match_token with parser, token_type

    If matches is equal to 1:
        proc advance with parser
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Error handling
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: had_error = 1

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing (Precedence Climbing)
Note: ============================================================================

Note: R Operator Precedence (lowest to highest):
Note: 1. Assignment: <-, <<-, =, ->, ->>
Note: 2. Pipe: |>, %>%
Note: 3. Formula: ~
Note: 4. Logical OR: ||, |
Note: 5. Logical AND: &&, &
Note: 6. Relational: <, >, <=, >=, ==, !=
Note: 7. Addition: +, -
Note: 8. Multiplication: *, /, %%, %/%
Note: 9. Custom infix: %anything%
Note: 10. Sequence: :
Note: 11. Unary: !, -, +
Note: 12. Exponentiation: ^, **
Note: 13. Namespace: ::, :::
Note: 14. Member access: $, @
Note: 15. Indexing: [...], [[...]]
Note: 16. Function call: (...)

@Reasoning:
Precedence table for R's Pratt parser. Drives parse_binary - higher numbers bind tighter. R's idiosyncrasies are reflected here: assignment (<-, ->, =) has very low precedence; the formula operator ~ sits between assignment and OR; %op% infix operators land at the same level as multiplication.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switch-like cascade over the input token type returning an integer precedence (0 means "not an operator"). Mirrors R Language Definition section 10.4.2 precedence list.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_precedence" takes token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get operator precedence level

    @Reasoning:
    R has unique operator precedence with special operators like <-,
    %>%, and custom %% operators. Formula (~) has lower precedence
    than most operators but higher than assignment.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Assignment operators (lowest precedence)
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_SUPER_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_SUPER_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Pipe operators
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
        Return 2
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_MAGRITTR_PIPE:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Formula
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_TILDE:
        Return 3
    End If

    Note: Logical OR
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_OR:
        Return 4
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_OR:
        Return 4
    End If

    Note: Logical AND
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_AND:
        Return 5
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LOGICAL_AND:
        Return 5
    End If

    Note: Relational operators
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LESS:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_GREATER:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return 6
    End If

    Note: Addition/Subtraction
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
        Return 7
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        Return 7
    End If

    Note: Multiplication/Division
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_STAR:
        Return 8
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_SLASH:
        Return 8
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT:
        Return 8
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_INT_DIV:
        Return 8
    End If

    Note: Custom infix operators
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_PERCENT_OP:
        Return 9
    End If

    Note: Sequence operator
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        Return 10
    End If

    Note: Exponentiation (right-associative)
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_CARET:
        Return 12
    End If

    Note: Namespace operators
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
        Return 13
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_TRIPLE_COLON:
        Return 13
    End If

    Note: Member access
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOLLAR:
        Return 14
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_AT:
        Return 14
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a binary operator
End Process

@Reasoning:
R has exactly four right-associative operators: ^ (power), <- and <<- (left-assign), -> and ->> (right-assign), and = (when used as assignment). Knowing this is required so parse_binary can fold associativity correctly: a^b^c parses as a^(b^c), and x<-y<-z parses as x<-(y<-z).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 only for TOKEN_CARET (power), TOKEN_LEFT_ASSIGN, TOKEN_LEFT_SUPER_ASSIGN, TOKEN_RIGHT_ASSIGN, TOKEN_RIGHT_SUPER_ASSIGN, and TOKEN_EQUAL_ASSIGN. Returns 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_right_associative" takes token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if operator is right-associative

    @Reasoning:
    R has right-associative operators: assignment operators (<-, =, etc.),
    exponentiation (^, **), and the formula operator (~).
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Assignment operators are right-associative
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_SUPER_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_SUPER_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL_ASSIGN:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Exponentiation is right-associative
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_CARET:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Formula is right-associative
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_TILDE:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Primary Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entry point for the leaf level of R's Pratt parser. Dispatches on the current token to recognize literals (numbers, strings, TRUE/FALSE/NA/NULL/Inf/NaN), identifiers, grouped expressions (paren-enclosed), function definitions, block expressions ({...}), vector literals (c(...)), and unary prefix operators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switch over current_token type: numeric/string literals build leaf nodes; "(" recursively calls parse_expression and consumes ")"; "{" delegates to parse_block; "function" -> parse_function_definition; identifier -> bare reference; otherwise unary prefix dispatched through parse_unary.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_primary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse primary expression

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Literals
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NUMBER:
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_NUMBER
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMPLEX:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_COMPLEX
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_STRING
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_TRUE
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_FALSE
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NULL:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_NULL
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NA:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_NA
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NAN:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_NAN
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_INF:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_INF
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Identifiers
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Grouped expression
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
        proc advance with parser
        Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"
        Return expr
    End If

    Note: Vector/List literal c(...)
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Let is_c be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "c"

        If is_c is equal to 1:
            Let next_token be proc peek_token with parser, 1
            If next_token is not equal to 0:
                Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0
                If next_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
                    Return proc parse_vector with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Function definition
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION:
        Return proc parse_function_definition with parser
    End If

    Note: Lambda (backslash syntax)
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_BACKSLASH:
        Return proc parse_lambda with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Postfix Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Wraps a primary expression with any number of trailing postfix constructs: function call f(...), single-bracket index x[...], double-bracket index x[[...]], $ member access, @ S4 slot access, and :: / ::: namespace access. Postfix operators all left-associate so a loop handles chains like df$col[1:5].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls parse_primary, then loops re-dispatching on the next token: TOKEN_LPAREN -> parse_call, TOKEN_LBRACKET -> parse_index, TOKEN_DOUBLE_LBRACKET -> parse_double_index, TOKEN_DOLLAR -> parse_member_access, TOKEN_AT -> parse_slot_access, TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON or TOKEN_TRIPLE_COLON -> parse_namespace.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_postfix" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse postfix expressions (calls, indexing, member access)

    Let expr be proc parse_primary with parser

    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse postfix operators in a loop
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Return expr
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        Note: Function call
        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN:
            Set expr to proc parse_call with parser, expr
            Note: Continue loop
        Otherwise:
            Note: Indexing [...]
            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET:
                Set expr to proc parse_index with parser, expr
                Note: Continue loop
            Otherwise:
                Note: Double indexing [[...]]
                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_LEFT_BRACKET:
                    Set expr to proc parse_double_index with parser, expr
                    Note: Continue loop
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Member access ($)
                    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOLLAR:
                        Set expr to proc parse_member_access with parser, expr
                        Note: Continue loop
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Slot access (@)
                        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_AT:
                            Set expr to proc parse_slot_access with parser, expr
                            Note: Continue loop
                        Otherwise:
                            Note: Namespace access (::, :::)
                            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
                                Set expr to proc parse_namespace with parser, expr, 0
                                Note: Continue loop
                            Otherwise:
                                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_TRIPLE_COLON:
                                    Set expr to proc parse_namespace with parser, expr, 1
                                    Note: Continue loop
                                Otherwise:
                                    Note: No more postfix operators
                                    Return expr
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Call, Index, and Member Access Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses an R function call `callee(arg1, name=arg2, ...)`. R supports both positional and named arguments and either may appear in any order. The callee has already been parsed by parse_postfix and is passed in.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "(", then loops parsing arguments separated by ",". Each argument may be `name = expr` (detected by lookahead at identifier + "=") or a bare expression. Each parsed argument is added as a child to a TOKEN_CALL node whose first child is the callee. Closing ")" is then consumed.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_call" takes parser as Integer, callee as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function call

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_CALL
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, callee  Note: Set callee as left child

    Note: Parse arguments (positional or name=value, comma-separated)
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Note: Parse first argument
            Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser
            If arg is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, arg
            End If

            Note: Parse remaining arguments. Forward progress is guaranteed:
            Note: every iteration either consumes a comma + one argument or
            Note: stops at the first non-comma token, so the loop cannot spin.
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set arg to proc parse_expression with parser
                    If arg is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with node, arg
                    End If
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0  Note: Not a comma - stop argument list
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses single-bracket indexing `object[i, j, drop=FALSE]`. R's single-bracket indexing returns a sub-structure preserving the original class (data frames remain data frames). Empty indices (`x[, 1]`) are legal and mean "all rows".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "[", loops parsing comma-separated index expressions (allowing empty slots between commas), and adds each as a child of a NODE_INDEX whose first child is the object. Consumes "]" at end.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_index" takes parser as Integer, object as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse indexing [...]

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, "Expected '['"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_INDEX
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, object  Note: Set object as left child

    Note: Parse indices (can be multiple, comma-separated)
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET:
            Note: Parse first index
            Let index be proc parse_expression with parser
            If index is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, index
            End If

            Note: Parse remaining indices
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set index to proc parse_expression with parser
                    If index is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with node, index
                    End If
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0  Note: Break
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, "Expected ']'"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses double-bracket indexing `x[[i]]`. Distinct from single-bracket: returns the raw element rather than a sub-structure (a list's [[i]] returns the contained value, not a single-element list).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes TOKEN_DOUBLE_LBRACKET, parses one or two comma-separated index expressions (R requires at least one), adds them as children of NODE_DOUBLE_INDEX, then consumes TOKEN_DOUBLE_RBRACKET.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_double_index" takes parser as Integer, object as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse double indexing [[...]]

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_LEFT_BRACKET, "Expected '[[''"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_DOUBLE_INDEX
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, object  Note: Set object as left child

    Note: Parse index
    Let index be proc parse_expression with parser
    If index is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, index  Note: Set index as right child
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_RIGHT_BRACKET, "Expected ']]'"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses R list/dataframe member access `obj$field`. Unlike most languages, the field name in R is NOT a quoted string but a bare identifier (or a backtick-quoted identifier for names with special characters).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the "$" token, then captures the next identifier or backtick-quoted name as the field name. Builds NODE_MEMBER_ACCESS with object as left child and the field name as right child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_member_access" takes parser as Integer, object as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse member access ($)

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_DOLLAR, "Expected '$'"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_MEMBER_ACCESS
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, object  Note: Set object as left child

    Note: Parse member name (identifier or string)
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let member be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
            Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with member, 8, lexeme
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, member  Note: Set member as right child
            proc advance with parser
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_STRING:
                Set member to proc create_node with NODE_STRING
                Set lexeme to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with member, 8, lexeme
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, member
                proc advance with parser
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses S4 slot access `obj@slotname`. S4 is R's formal object system; slots are typed and accessed via @ rather than $.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "@", captures the next identifier as the slot name, builds NODE_SLOT_ACCESS with object as left child and slot name as right child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_slot_access" takes parser as Integer, object as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse slot access (@) for S4 objects

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_AT, "Expected '@'"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_SLOT_ACCESS
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, object  Note: Set object as left child

    Note: Parse slot name (identifier)
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let slot be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
            Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with slot, 8, lexeme
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, slot  Note: Set slot as right child
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses package namespace access `pkg::fn` (exported) or `pkg:::fn` (internal). The is_internal flag tells the caller which form was matched so it can build the right node type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already consumed the package identifier; consumes the "::" or ":::" token via the is_internal switch, then captures the symbol identifier. Builds NODE_NAMESPACE_EXPORTED or NODE_NAMESPACE_INTERNAL accordingly.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_namespace" takes parser as Integer, package as Integer, is_internal as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse namespace access (:: or :::)

    If is_internal is equal to 0:
        proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, "Expected '::'"
    Otherwise:
        proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_TRIPLE_COLON, "Expected ':::'"
    End If

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_NAMESPACE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, package  Note: Set package as left child
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, is_internal  Note: Store internal flag in token_type field

    Note: Parse function/object name
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Let name be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
            Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with name, 8, lexeme
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, name  Note: Set name as right child
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Unary Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses R prefix unary operators: -, +, !, and ~ (one-sided formula). Right-associative by definition - --x means -(-x). Falls through to parse_postfix when no unary token is present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Checks current token for TOKEN_MINUS, TOKEN_PLUS, TOKEN_NOT, TOKEN_TILDE. If present, advances, recursively calls parse_unary to build the operand, and wraps in a NODE_UNARY_OP with the operator token type stored. Otherwise delegates to parse_postfix.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_unary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse unary expression

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return proc parse_postfix with parser
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Unary operators: !, -, +
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_BANG:
        proc advance with parser
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, RLexer.TOKEN_BANG
        Let operand be proc parse_unary with parser
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, operand  Note: Set operand as right child
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        proc advance with parser
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, RLexer.TOKEN_MINUS
        Set operand to proc parse_unary with parser
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, operand
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
        proc advance with parser
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_UNARY_OP
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, RLexer.TOKEN_PLUS
        Set operand to proc parse_unary with parser
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, operand
        Return node
    End If

    Return proc parse_postfix with parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Binary Expression Parsing (Precedence Climbing)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pratt/precedence-climbing core. Folds left-hand operand with successive binary operators whose precedence >= min_precedence. Right-associativity is handled by recursing with the same precedence rather than precedence+1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Starts with parse_unary for the left operand, then loops: peek operator, get_precedence; if below min, exit. Otherwise advance, recurse parse_binary with prec+1 (or prec for right-assoc per is_right_associative), and combine into NODE_BINARY_OP with token_type set.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in total tokens because each operator is consumed exactly once; recursion depth bounded by precedence-level count (~15).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_binary" takes parser as Integer, min_precedence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse binary expression with precedence climbing

    @Reasoning:
    Uses precedence climbing algorithm to handle R's complex operator
    precedence including right-associative operators (<-, ^) and
    special operators (|>, %>%, ~).
    @End Reasoning

    Let left be proc parse_unary with parser

    If left is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        Let precedence be proc get_precedence with token_type

        If precedence is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        If precedence is less than min_precedence:
            Return left
        End If

        Note: Consume operator
        proc advance with parser

        Note: Determine next min precedence (handle right-associativity)
        Let next_min be precedence plus 1
        Let is_right_assoc be proc is_right_associative with token_type

        If is_right_assoc is equal to 1:
            Set next_min to precedence  Note: Right-associative
        End If

        Note: Parse right operand
        Let right be proc parse_binary with parser, next_min

        If right is equal to 0:
            Return left
        End If

        Note: Create binary operation node
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_BINARY_OP
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, token_type  Note: Store operator type
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, left
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, right

        Set left to node
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level expression entry point. Delegates to parse_binary with min_precedence=0 so any operator can be folded in. All other parse rules ultimately route through here when they need a full expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the result of parse_binary(parser, 0).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete expression (entry point)

    Note: Start with lowest precedence (0) to parse all operators
    Return proc parse_binary with parser, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function Definition Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses an R function literal `function(args) body`. In R, function definitions are expressions, so the result can be assigned (`f <- function(x) x+1`) or passed inline. Default argument values are supported via `function(x = 5)`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_FUNCTION; consumes "(", loops parsing parameters via parse_parameter separated by ",", consumes ")", then parses body via parse_expression (a single expression or a brace-block). Builds NODE_FUNCTION_DEF with parameter list as children and body as right child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_function_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function definition: function(x, y = default, ...) { body }

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_FUNCTION, "Expected 'function'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_FUNCTION_DEF

    Note: Parse parameters
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Note: Parse first parameter
            Let param be proc parse_parameter with parser
            If param is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, param
            End If

            Note: Parse remaining parameters
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set param to proc parse_parameter with parser
                    If param is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with node, param
                    End If
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0  Note: Break
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Note: Parse body (can be single expression or block)
    Let body be proc parse_statement with parser
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, body  Note: Store body as right child

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses one formal parameter in a function definition: either `name` (required) or `name = default` (optional with default value). Also recognises `...` as the variadic parameter sentinel.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures the parameter identifier (or TOKEN_TRIPLE_DOT for variadic). If followed by "=", consumes it and calls parse_expression to capture the default value. Returns a NODE_PARAMETER with name as left, default as right (or 0 if none).
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_parameter" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function parameter (with optional default value)

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Check for ... (varargs)
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT:
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, proc string_from_literal with "..."
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Parameter name
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let param_name be proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with param_name, 8, lexeme
        proc advance with parser

        Note: Check for default value
        Set token to proc current_token with parser
        If token is not equal to 0:
            Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EQUAL_ASSIGN:
                proc advance with parser

                Note: Create assignment node for default value
                Let assign_node be proc create_node with NODE_ASSIGN
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with assign_node, 16, param_name
                Let default_value be proc parse_expression with parser
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with assign_node, 24, default_value

                Return assign_node
            End If
        End If

        Return param_name
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lambda Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses R 4.1+ backslash lambda syntax `\(x) x+1`, a more concise alternative to `function(x) x+1`. Otherwise identical semantics to parse_function_definition - same parameter list and body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_BACKSLASH; consumes "(", loops parsing parameters via parse_parameter separated by ",", consumes ")", parses the body expression. Builds NODE_LAMBDA with parameters as children and body as right child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_lambda" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse lambda: \(x, y) expression

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_BACKSLASH, "Expected '\\'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_LAMBDA

    Note: Parse parameters
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Note: Parse first parameter
            Let param be proc parse_parameter with parser
            If param is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, param
            End If

            Note: Parse remaining parameters
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set param to proc parse_parameter with parser
                    If param is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with node, param
                    End If
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0  Note: Break
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Note: Parse body expression
    Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, body  Note: Store body as right child

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Vector/List Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses R's vector constructor `c(...)`. Although c() is a function call, the lexer and parser handle it as a dedicated form so vector literals can be optimized later (e.g. unboxing for numeric vectors).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_C; consumes "(", loops parsing comma-separated expressions which may be `name=value` or bare. Each element becomes a child of NODE_VECTOR. Consumes ")" at end.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_vector" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse vector literal: c(1, 2, 3)

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected 'c'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_VECTOR

    Note: Parse elements
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN:
            Note: Parse first element
            Let elem be proc parse_expression with parser
            If elem is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with node, elem
            End If

            Note: Parse remaining elements
            Set token to proc current_token with parser
            While token is not equal to 0:
                Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                    proc advance with parser
                    Set elem to proc parse_expression with parser
                    If elem is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with node, elem
                    End If
                    Set token to proc current_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set token to 0  Note: Break
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Dispatches to the appropriate statement parser based on the leading keyword: if -> parse_if_statement, while -> parse_while_statement, for -> parse_for_statement, repeat -> parse_repeat_statement, "{" -> parse_block. Falls through to parse_expression because R has no statement/expression dichotomy - everything is an expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switch over current token type checking for control-flow keywords. Each branch advances past the keyword and delegates to the dedicated parse helper. Default branch returns parse_expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse statement

    Let token be proc current_token with parser

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Control flow statements
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Return proc parse_if_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_WHILE:
        Return proc parse_while_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        Return proc parse_for_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_REPEAT:
        Return proc parse_repeat_statement with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_BREAK:
        Let node be proc create_node with NODE_BREAK_STMT
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NEXT:
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_NEXT_STMT
        proc advance with parser
        Return node
    End If

    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RETURN:
        proc advance with parser
        Set node to proc create_node with NODE_RETURN_STMT

        Note: Parse return value if present
        Set token to proc current_token with parser
        If token is not equal to 0:
            Set token_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

            Note: Check if not end of statement
            If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
                    If token_type is not equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
                        Let value be proc parse_expression with parser
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, value
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Return node
    End If

    Note: Block statement
    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE:
        Return proc parse_block with parser
    End If

    Note: Expression statement
    Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser

    If expr is not equal to 0:
        Let stmt_node be proc create_node with NODE_EXPRESSION_STMT
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with stmt_node, 16, expr
        Return stmt_node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `if (cond) then_expr else else_expr`. The else branch is optional. R treats if as an expression returning the chosen branch's value, which is why it uses parse_expression for the body rather than block parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_IF; consumes "(", parses condition via parse_expression, consumes ")". Parses then-branch as a statement. If TOKEN_ELSE follows, advances and parses the else-branch. Builds NODE_IF with condition as left, then as middle (child[0]), else as right.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if statement: if (condition) then_branch else else_branch

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_IF, "Expected 'if'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Let then_branch be proc parse_statement with parser

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_IF_STMT
    proc add_child with node, condition
    proc add_child with node, then_branch

    Note: Check for else clause
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
            proc advance with parser
            Let else_branch be proc parse_statement with parser
            proc add_child with node, else_branch
        End If
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `while (cond) body`. Like if, the body is a single statement (often a block). Returns NULL invisibly at runtime, but at parse time we just build the AST node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_WHILE; consumes "(", parses condition, consumes ")", parses body via parse_statement. Builds NODE_WHILE with condition as left and body as right.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while statement: while (condition) body

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_WHILE, "Expected 'while'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Let body be proc parse_statement with parser

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_WHILE_STMT
    proc add_child with node, condition
    proc add_child with node, body

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses `for (var in iterable) body`. R's for is iterator-based - var is bound to each element of iterable in turn. The variable is created in the enclosing environment and persists after the loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_FOR; consumes "(", captures the loop variable identifier, consumes TOKEN_IN, parses iterable via parse_expression, consumes ")", then parses body via parse_statement. Builds NODE_FOR with variable as left, iterable as middle child, body as right.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse for statement: for (var in sequence) body

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_FOR, "Expected 'for'"
    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "Expected '('"

    Note: Parse loop variable
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let var_node be 0

    If token is not equal to 0:
        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Set var_node to proc create_node with NODE_IDENTIFIER
            Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with var_node, 8, lexeme
            proc advance with parser
        End If
    End If

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_IN, "Expected 'in'"

    Note: Parse sequence
    Let sequence be proc parse_expression with parser

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Note: Parse body
    Let body be proc parse_statement with parser

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_FOR_STMT
    proc add_child with node, var_node
    proc add_child with node, sequence
    proc add_child with node, body

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses R's `repeat body` - an unconditional infinite loop terminated only by `break` or `return`. R has no do-while; repeat is the idiomatic loop when the exit condition is computed inside the body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_REPEAT; immediately parses body via parse_statement (no parentheses, no condition expression). Builds NODE_REPEAT with body as right child.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_repeat_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse repeat statement: repeat body (infinite loop, use break to exit)

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_REPEAT, "Expected 'repeat'"

    Let body be proc parse_statement with parser

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_REPEAT_STMT
    proc add_child with node, body

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a brace-delimited block `{ stmt1; stmt2; ... }`. Statements may be separated by semicolons or newlines. The block's value is the value of its last statement, matching R's everything-is-an-expression semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Already saw TOKEN_LBRACE; loops parsing statements via parse_statement until TOKEN_RBRACE is seen. Statement separators (TOKEN_SEMICOLON, TOKEN_NEWLINE) are consumed between statements. Each parsed statement is added as a child of NODE_BLOCK. Consumes "}" at end.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse block statement: { statements }

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE, "Expected '{'"

    Let node be proc create_node with NODE_BLOCK

    Note: Parse statements until closing brace or EOF. A forward-progress guard
    Note: captures the cursor each iteration and breaks if parse_statement failed
    Note: to advance, so a malformed token can never spin the loop.
    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE:
                Set looping to 0
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
                    proc advance with parser
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                        proc advance with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Let pos_before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                        If stmt is not equal to 0:
                            proc add_child with node, stmt
                        End If
                        Let pos_after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        If pos_after is equal to pos_before:
                            Note: No forward progress - force-advance to avoid a spin
                            proc advance with parser
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc consume with parser, RLexer.TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE, "Expected '}'"

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Program Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry called once per source file. Builds a NODE_PROGRAM whose children are the sequence of top-level statements until EOF. This is the AST root returned to r_semantic / r_to_hir.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates NODE_PROGRAM. Loops while current_token is not EOF: skips separator tokens (semicolons, newlines), then calls parse_statement and adds the result as a child of NODE_PROGRAM. Returns the program node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in token count; the dominant cost is the cascade of parse rules (Pratt parsing is linear in the input).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse complete R program (top-level statements)

    @Reasoning:
    R programs are sequences of top-level statements and expressions.
    Unlike many languages, R allows bare expressions at the top level
    which are evaluated and their results printed.
    @End Reasoning

    Let program be proc create_node with NODE_PROGRAM

    Note: Parse top-level statements until EOF. The forward-progress guard
    Note: mirrors parse_block: if parse_statement fails to consume any token we
    Note: force one advance so an unparseable token cannot spin the loop.
    Let looping be 1
    While looping is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser

        If token is equal to 0:
            Set looping to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

            If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Set looping to 0
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_NEWLINE:
                    proc advance with parser
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to RLexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                        proc advance with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Let pos_before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
                        If stmt is not equal to 0:
                            proc add_child with program, stmt
                        End If
                        Let pos_after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
                        If pos_after is equal to pos_before:
                            proc advance with parser
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Post-tokenization unescape pass for string literals. The lexer captures the raw lexeme including backslash sequences; this routine produces the decoded string for the AST node so codegen can emit the right bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the input string, copying bytes verbatim until a backslash is seen. Then dispatches: \n -> 10, \t -> 9, \r -> 13, \\ -> 92, \' -> 39, \" -> 34, \0 -> 0, \xNN -> hex byte, \uNNNN -> UTF-8 encoding. Unknown escapes are passed through verbatim (lenient like R itself).
@End Implementation

Process called "process_escape_sequences" takes input as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Process escape sequences in string literals
    @Reasoning
    R supports standard escape sequences like newline, tab, carriage return, backslash, quotes, etc.
    This scans the input string byte-by-byte and produces an output string with the escape
    sequences converted to their actual character values. Allocates a fresh buffer sized to
    the original input length since escape processing can only shrink or equal input length.
    The output is null-terminated.
    @End Reasoning

    If input is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let input_length be proc string_length from StringCore with input
    If input_length is equal to 0:
        Return input
    End If

    Let output be proc allocate from Layout with input_length plus 1
    If output is equal to 0:
        Return input
    End If

    Let out_pos be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than input_length:
        Let current_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with input, i
        If current_char is equal to 92:
            Let has_next be 0
            Let next_index be i plus 1
            If next_index is less than input_length:
                Set has_next to 1
            End If
            If has_next is equal to 1:
                Let next_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with input, next_index
                Let mapped be next_char
                If next_char is equal to 110:
                    Set mapped to 10
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 116:
                    Set mapped to 9
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 114:
                    Set mapped to 13
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 98:
                    Set mapped to 8
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 102:
                    Set mapped to 12
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 118:
                    Set mapped to 11
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 97:
                    Set mapped to 7
                End If
                If next_char is equal to 48:
                    Set mapped to 0
                End If
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with output, out_pos, mapped
                Set out_pos to out_pos plus 1
                Set i to i plus 2
            Otherwise:
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with output, out_pos, 92
                Set out_pos to out_pos plus 1
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with output, out_pos, current_char
            Set out_pos to out_pos plus 1
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with output, out_pos, 0
    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Strips the surrounding quote characters from a string literal lexeme and decodes its escape sequences. Yields the canonical string value to be stored in the AST node's value field.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips the leading quote, captures the body up to (but not including) the closing quote, then runs process_escape_sequences on the body to expand escapes. Returns the heap-allocated decoded string.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_from_literal" takes literal as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a processed string from a source-level string literal
    @Reasoning
    Helper to normalize raw string literals coming from the R source into Runa strings.
    Simply forwards to process_escape_sequences which handles the full escape-sequence
    processing. The input literal should already have any enclosing quotes stripped by
    the lexer before being passed here. Returns a freshly allocated processed string.
    @End Reasoning

    If literal is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc process_escape_sequences with literal
End Process
